<paragraph blockId="45.[264,1323,284,1195]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Etymology. Latin, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Marascia" authorityYear="2003" box="[532,644,810,835]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnipes">
<emphasis box="[532,644,810,835]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">magnipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, for ‘large foot,’ referring to the large podiform male terminalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[264,1323,284,1195]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Remarks. In addition to the characters in the key, the yellowish scape and pedicel, yellow base of the proboscis, and mostly yellow tarsi distinguish 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Marascia" authorityYear="2003" box="[1008,1157,929,954]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnipes">
<emphasis box="[1008,1157,929,954]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">O. magnipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Mystax with abundant, long, white setae, yellow postocular bristles, the slightly concave ventral margin of the middle femur and its vestiture, the long, thin anteroventral bristles on the hind femur, fringe of short, white setae on the fore tibia and fore tarsus, stout bristles on sternites 3­5 further characterize the male. The shape of the spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[1107,1209,1089,1115]" captionStart="FIGURES 165­172" captionStartId="84.[264,382,1785,1809]" captionTargetBox="[280,1303,318,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-52@84.[254,1313,310,1675]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="FIGURES 165­172. Male terminalia of Ommatius magnipes, sp. n. 165­167. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 168. Gonostylus; 169. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 170. Spermatheca; 171. Genital fork; 172. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019095/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 170</figureCitation>
) and one unusually long bristle in the apical corner of sternite 8 (
<figureCitation box="[929,1030,1129,1155]" captionStart="FIGURES 165­172" captionStartId="84.[264,382,1785,1809]" captionTargetBox="[280,1303,318,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-52@84.[254,1313,310,1675]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="FIGURES 165­172. Male terminalia of Ommatius magnipes, sp. n. 165­167. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 168. Gonostylus; 169. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 170. Spermatheca; 171. Genital fork; 172. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019095/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 172</figureCitation>
) further characterize the female.
</paragraph>
